<br>
rumor 1- police numerical code for a marijuana-related crime<br>
rumor 2- in Marin or Humboldt County, they started some festival on April 20, I forget the story, but I have friends tell me firsthand that's where it started<br>
<br>
Marijuana has medicinal benefits (glaucoma, appetite issues from chemo or diet conditions (B, AN), and some other limited applications, but smoking is carcinogenic, so the benefit is traded off b/c you pollute your lungs- so eat it, or use a water pipe.  Synthetic THC can actually be more potent than street varieties... interesting.  A recent Canadian study on youth development and IQ (which isn't a good measure, but I digress) discovered that heavy use during development can lower IQ, but that mild use during development (puberty) raised IQ.<br>
<br>
Very soon, you will note a general shift of marijuana laws and Federal policy, due to actions by states like Arizona, California, and Washington... to name a few.  Canada is a neat place for this reason too-- one of the main reasons you'll catch me in BC is actually for the snow and wilderness, but the BC Hydro (I am told) is very kind.  <br>
<br>
The problem with pot, like a lot of substances, is that it's psychologically addictive.  And b/c it's largely a white person's domain (e.g., typical hippie = white, typical trustafarian = white), I think you'll see it tolerated more and more, unlike crack cocaine, where with a few too many grams, you get 10 years mandatory (versus need like 5 tons of powder cocaine).  Yes, I just played the race card, it so powa (trump!).<br>
<br>
It's a fun debate, and counterforces are gathering, so we will see some societal trends shift one way or the other.<br>
<br>
1st law in USA was the Federal Marijuana Tax Stamp, which attempted to heavily tariff hemp trade, and then it turned more War on Drugs like, in the 1950s and on.  And 1970s, came the F.C.S.A - which schedules substances-- pot = schedule I, while coke is schedule II (it's technically prescribable).  Pot users and dealers have gone to prison by truckloads since then- if they got caught and didn't turn state's witness (=rat) for a lenient sentence.  Under RICO, they can seize and forfeit all a convict's assets, as long as they demonstrate a link to the assets to drug money.<br>
<br>
Anyway, just trying to inform.  If you are a true Rastaman and like to toke, and do not do the coke, then sound smart and reiterate some of the above info.  Credibility helps.  <br>
<br>
Me personally, don't touch the stuff, but I live in one of the &quot;hippie/yuppie towns&quot; and know that it's a subculture, and I can tolerate that.  If ya get caught, get a good lawyer, cause DAs are usually good too, and it's their job to help incarcerate people.  No EQ in jail I assume hehe.<br>
